WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.280
Let's create a blog from scratch with Quarto and then publish it out to the web.

00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:12.700
So inside rstudio, I'm going to create a new project, new directory, new Quarto blog.

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:20.020
We'll create that new session, let it switch over to the new environment, and now we're going to test building it locally.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:26.559
Quarto has gone ahead and created a bunch of different files that create the Quarto blog and all the different kind of hello world examples.

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:33.820
We can see those locally just by checking on the build tab and click render website, and that will build the blog.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:40.560
We can see that we have a functioning blog, a post with code, as well as things like an about me page.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:45.840
So I have this locally, but I can also say I want to publish this to the web. Inside rstudio,

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:47.840
I can go down to the console pane.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.139
I'm going to click over on the terminal or the command line interface and do Quarto Publish.

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:58.900
This is going to provide me with a few options. You can publish to Quarto Pub, which is a free service that we provide.

00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:03.259
I'm going to do that because I already have it set up. It's going to ask which account do you want to use?

00:01:03.259 --> 00:01:07.260
I already have an account on here, but if you don't have an account, it'll ask you to sign up.

00:01:07.739 --> 00:01:14.260
I'll click enter, and it's going to publish that to Quarto Pub with a specific name, in this case testblog2.

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:18.300
I'll click enter, and it's going to use all that information and put it out on the web.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:24.059
While it does all this, it's going to build all the website again, all the blog posts and everything together,

00:01:25.019 --> 00:01:30.099
re-render all those different components, and then ship it out to the web. In the span of this little speed run,

00:01:30.099 --> 00:01:35.820
we can go from no blog to new blog to blog on the internet and go and look at it.

00:01:35.820 --> 00:01:39.379
And now we have a blog post that we can share and a blog to share with the world.

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:45.720
To learn more about using Quarto as a computational notebook for technical or scientific communication,

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.959
please check out the resources at quarto.org. Thanks!

